Internal Event Model (Monolith now, Kafka later) – Locked Specification

Scope

This document locks the internal event model for the modular monolith now (in-process via interfaces), with a clear path to Kafka later.

It defines:
	•	Event goals and boundaries
	•	Which events exist per module
	•	Where they are published
	•	Sync vs async handling
	•	Idempotency rules
	•	After-commit publishing
	•	Outbox timing decision

⸻

1) Goals & Semantics (Locked)

1.1 Purpose

Events are used to:
	•	Decouple modules inside the monolith
	•	Trigger side effects (notifications, cache purges, analytics-style counters)

Audit logging remains DB-based as previously locked.

1.2 Delivery semantics
	•	Event handling is designed for at-least-once semantics.
	•	Therefore handlers must be idempotent.

⸻

2) Transport & Wiring (Locked)

2.1 Publisher style
	•	Use per-module publisher interfaces (not a generic proxy bus).

Examples:
	•	OrderEvents
	•	PaymentEvents
	•	CatalogEvents
	•	SiteEvents
	•	AuthEvents

2.2 Sync vs async
	•	Sync for invariants when needed (rare): immediate, in-request.
	•	Async for side effects (default): notifications, cache purges, webhooks dispatch, metrics.

⸻

3) Event Naming & Payload (Locked)

3.1 Naming
	•	Past tense domain events:
	•	OrderConfirmed, PaymentSucceeded, ProductArchived

Optional Kafka-friendly key naming:
	•	order.confirmed, payment.succeeded (for later)

3.2 Event payload strategy
	•	Minimal payload is required to avoid coupling.

All events include:
	•	eventId (UUID)
	•	occurredAt (UTC ISO timestamp)
	•	tenantId (UUID)
	•	actorUserId (UUID, nullable)
	•	entityType (string)
	•	entityId (UUID)
	•	data (small JSON object)

Consumers fetch additional detail from DB if needed.

⸻

4) Idempotency Rules (Locked)

4.1 Primary rule
	•	Every handler must be idempotent.

4.2 Event identity
	•	Every event has eventId = UUID.
	•	For duplicate-prone side effects, events may include an idempotencyKey in data, e.g.:
	•	ORDER:{orderId}:CONFIRMED:v1
	•	PAYMENT_ATTEMPT:{attemptId}:PAID:v1

4.3 Consumption tracking (minimal)

For side effects that must not duplicate (emails, external webhooks):
	•	Use a DB table to dedupe processing:

CREATE TABLE event_consumptions (
  id UUID PRIMARY KEY,
  consumer_name TEXT NOT NULL,
  event_id UUID NOT NULL,
  processed_at TIMESTAMPTZ NOT NULL DEFAULT now(),
  UNIQUE (consumer_name, event_id)
);


⸻

5) Transaction Boundary: After-Commit Publishing (Locked)

5.1 Publishing timing
	•	Domain events are published after DB commit using transaction synchronization hooks.

5.2 Rationale
	•	Prevents: event emitted while DB transaction later rolls back.
	•	Keeps behavior aligned with future outbox patterns.

⸻

6) Outbox Decision (Locked)

6.1 MVP decision
	•	No outbox in MVP.

6.2 When outbox becomes required

Implement outbox when:
	•	Kafka (or another broker) is introduced, OR
	•	You need guaranteed delivery across crashes for critical side effects.

⸻

7) Module Event Catalog (Locked)

7.1 Orders module

Published by OrderService (after commit):
	•	OrderCreated
	•	OrderConfirmed
	•	OrderFulfillmentStatusChanged
	•	OrderCancelled
	•	OrderRefunded

Common data examples:
	•	status transitions: { "from": "NEW", "to": "CONFIRMED" }

⸻

7.2 Payments module

Published by PaymentService (after commit):
	•	PaymentAttemptCreated
	•	PaymentSucceeded
	•	PaymentFailed
	•	PaymentRefunded

Locked decision:
	•	Payment service updates orders.payment_status directly (simplest MVP).
	•	Events are still emitted for side effects.

⸻

7.3 Store/Catalog module

Published by CatalogService (after commit):
	•	ProductCreated
	•	ProductUpdated
	•	ProductArchived
	•	CategoryCreated
	•	CategoryUpdated
	•	CategoryArchived
	•	ProductImagesChanged
	•	LinkedProductsUpdated

⸻

7.4 Site/Content Gateway module (Payload)

Published by ContentGatewayService (after commit):
	•	SiteSettingsUpdated
	•	PageUpdated
	•	SitePublished (future; optional now)

⸻

7.5 Auth/Membership module

Published by AuthService/MembershipService (after commit):
	•	UserInvited
	•	InviteAccepted
	•	MemberRoleChanged
	•	MemberDisabled
	•	PasswordResetRequested
	•	PasswordResetCompleted

⸻

8) Side-effect Consumers (Locked)

8.1 Notification module (minimal)
	•	A minimal Notification module exists to consume:
	•	invite/reset events
	•	order/payment events (future customer notifications)

Implementation can be:
	•	Email provider later
	•	Dev mode logs now

8.2 Cache invalidation
	•	Catalog and Site events trigger cache invalidation for public endpoints.

⸻

9) Kafka Migration Path (Locked)

When moving to Kafka:
	•	Keep event names and envelopes stable.
	•	Replace in-process publisher implementations with Kafka producers.
	•	Introduce Outbox for exactly-once-ish producer behavior.
	•	Keep handler idempotency and event_consumptions table (or equivalent).

⸻

10) Final Locked Summary
	•	Per-module event publisher interfaces
	•	Minimal event payload envelope with tenant & actor correlation
	•	At-least-once semantics → idempotent handlers required
	•	After-commit publishing is mandatory
	•	No outbox in MVP; implement when Kafka/guaranteed delivery becomes necessary
	•	Locked event catalog across Orders, Payments, Catalog, Site, Auth
	•	Notification module exists minimally; cache invalidation uses events

This specification is locked and implementation-ready.